# Memory rules

The team has four kinds of memory. Use them deliberately.

1. **Working docs** (`docs/`) - the current project's brief, research, plan, handoff,
   review. The live handoff bus between roles. Read upstream, write your own.

2. **Learnings** (`memory/learnings/`) - durable lessons that outlive one project.
   When you hit a correction, a non-obvious insight, a knowledge gap, or a
   best practice, append a short entry. Categories: correction | insight |
   knowledge_gap | best_practice. Never log secrets, tokens, or full config files.

3. **Capability map** (`memory/map/capability-map.md`) - the index of what exists:
   projects, modules, skills, and how they connect. Consult it before assuming
   something must be built from scratch. Update it when you add a module or skill.


4. **Doc index** (`memory/map/doc-index.md`) - the index of all existing project docs.
   Check this before opening any doc. Load only the specific file the current task
   needs. Never load all docs at once. This is how existing knowledge stays accessible
   without burning context tokens re-reading files every session.

Layer 0 (agentmemory) runs as the retrieval backend — it handles automatic session
recall and semantic search on top of these files. The files remain the source of truth.
If agentmemory is not running, fall back to local file reading only.

Keep entries short. Memory is only useful if it stays current and uncontradicted.
